e to Italy's native grapes and their wines. Writing with great enthusiasm and deep knowledge, D'Agata discusses more than five hundred different native Italian grape varieties, from Aglianico to Zibibbo. D'Agata provides details about how wine grapes are identified and classified, what clones are available, which soils are ideal, and what genetic evidence tells us about a variety's parentage. He gives historical and anecdotal accounts of each grape variety and describes the characteristics of wines made from the grape. A regional list of varieties and a list of the best producers provide additional guidance. Comprehensive, thoroughly researched, and engaging, this book is the perfect companion for anyone who wants to know more about the vast enological treasures cultivated in Italy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aGrapesxAnalysis. 0aGrapesxVarietiesxItaly. 0aGrapesxVarietieszItaly. 0aWine and wine makingxItaly. 0aWine and wine makingzItaly. 4aalcoholics. 4adiverse country. 4afood and drink. 4afoodies. 4agreat italian wines. 4agreek influence. 4ahistory of alcohol. 4aintro to wine. 4aitalys greatest wines. 4amicroclimate. 4anative grapes. 4aphoenician. 4aroman culture. 4asommelier. 4avineyard. 4avolcanic soil. 4awine country. 4awine guide. 4awinos. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Agriculture & Food (see also POLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Agriculture & Food Policy).2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311062111208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUCal Press eBook Package 2014-2016z978311065748740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/9780520957053423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520957053.jpg  a